Title : Ted Steinberg
Text : '''Ted Steinberg''' (born 1961) is Adeline Barry Davee Distinguished Professor of History and Professor of Law at [[Case Western Reserve University]].<ref>http://history.case.edu/faculty/ted-steinberg</ref>

Steinberg is the author of several books in [[History of the United States|U.S. history]] that focus on the relationship between ecological forces and social power. His best known works include ''Down to Earth: Nature’s Role in American History'' (2002); ''Acts of God: The Unnatural History of Natural Disaster in America'' (2000); and ''American Green: The Obsessive Quest for the Perfect Lawn'' (2006). His most recent book, ''Gotham Unbound: The Ecological History of Greater New York'' (2014), reinterprets the [[New York metropolitan area]]’s history from an environmental perspective and argues against the commonly held view that geography determined the city’s destiny. Considered by some to be an ecosocialist or pro-socialist scholar,<ref>{{cite web |url = http://climateandcapitalism.com/2017/09/05/what-are-the-essential-books-on-ecosocialism/|title = Ecosocialist Bookshelf: What are the essential books on ecosocialism?|publisher = Climate & Capitalism|accessdate=2017-12-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=AC|author2=JJ|date=2010-06-25|title=This quarter’s selection |journal=International Socialism: A quarterly review of socialist theory|issue=127|url=http://isj.org.uk/this-quarters-selection-summer-2010/}}</ref> Steinberg is highly critical of the impact that capitalism has had on the environment and society.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Steinberg, Ted|year=Spring 2010|title=Can Capitalism Save the Planet?: On the Origins of Green Liberalism|journal=Radical History Review |volume=107 |pages=7–24 |url=http://scalar.usc.edu/works/uiuc-macs410-media-information-ethics-/media/CanCapitalismSavePlanet_Steinberg.pdf |doi=10.1215/01636545-2009-032}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Steinberg, Ted|year=Winter 2017|title=Review of ''Easy On, Easy Off: The Urban Pathology of America’s Small Towns'' by Jack Williams |journal=Journal of Interdisciplinary History|volume=48|number=3|pages=425–426 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/678099}}</ref>

His books have received the following prizes: [[National Outdoor Book Award]] in the category of Nature & the Environment for ''Down to Earth: Nature’s Role in American History'', 2002;<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.noba-web.org/books02.htm|title = Winners of the 2002 National Outdoor Book Awards|publisher = National Outdoor Book Awards|accessdate=2017-12-06 }}</ref> [[Ohio Academy of History]]'s Publication Award for ''Acts of God: The Unnatural History of Natural Disaster in America'', 2001;<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.ohioacademyofhistory.org/2013/03/19/publication-award/|title = Publication Award|publisher = Ohio Academy of History|accessdate=2017-12-06 }}</ref> co-winner, the [[Law and Society Association]]'s J. Willard Hurst Prize for the best work in socio-legal history for ''Nature Incorporated: Industrialization and the Waters of New England'', 1992;<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.lawandsociety.org/prizes/hurst_winners.htm/|title =  James Willard Hurst Jr. Prize Winners|publisher = Law and Society Association|accessdate=2017-12-06 }}</ref> and the [[Old Sturbridge Village]] E. Harold Hugo Memorial Book Prize for the best book on the history and material culture of rural [[New England]] for ''Nature Incorporated'', 1992.

He also written for ''[[CounterPunch]]'', [[Dissent (American magazine)|''Dissent'']], ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'', [[Discover (magazine)|''Discover'']], ''[[Scientific American]]'', [[Natural History (magazine)|''Natural History'']], and ''[[The New York Times]]'' among others and has appeared on numerous radio and television shows including [[Freakonomics Radio]], [[Radio Times with Marty Moss-Coane]], [[The Leonard Lopate Show]], The [[Dennis Prager]] Show, The [[Michael Smerconish]] Show, [[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]], The [[Jerry Doyle]] Show, The [[T. D. Mischke|Mischke]] Broadcast, [[Martha Stewart Living Radio]], [[To the Best of Our Knowledge]], [[Penn & Teller]]: Bullshit and [[CBS News Sunday Morning]].<ref>http://tedsteinberg.com/about/</ref>

He has been the recipient of support from the Michigan Society of Fellows (1990–1993), the [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]] (1996), the [[American Council of Learned Societies]] Burkhardt Fellowship (2001), the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]] (2010), and [[Yale University]], where he was the B. Benjamin Zucker Fellow in 2006.

Steinberg opposes the market economy and capitalism.<ref>{{cite news|title=Capitalism, the State and the Drowning of America|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2017/09/08/capitalism-the-state-and-the-drowning-of-america/|publisher=Counterpunch|accessdate=2017-12-09|date=2017-09-08|first=Ted|last=Steinberg}}</ref> He has publicly advocated for [[Freedom of speech|free speech]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Show a Film, End Up on a Watch List|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2016/10/31/show-a-film-end-up-on-a-watch-list/|publisher=Counterpunch|accessdate=2017-12-06|date=2016-10-31|first=Ted|last=Steinberg}}</ref> and the rights of the [[Palestinians|Palestinian people]] living under [[Israeli-occupied territories|Israeli occupation]].  He supports the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] movement,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/opinion/index.ssf/2016/03/with_the_middle_east_peace_pro.html|title=With the Middle East peace process "dead," now what? Douglas Kerr and Ted Steinberg (Opinion)|date=March 23, 2016|publisher=Cleveland.com|accessdate=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ohio anti-BDS bill would hamper free speech and human rights activism, opponents say|url=https://columbusfreepress.com/article/ohio-anti-bds-bill-would-hamper-free-speech-and-human-rights-activism-opponents-say|publisher=Columbus Free Press|accessdate=2017-12-06|date=2016-07-28|first=Steve|last=Palm-Houser}}</ref> including the [[Academic boycott of Israel|boycott of Israeli academic institutions]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://historynewsnetwork.org/article/161644 |title = Response to Controversy over the Proposed Resolution Critical of Israel|date = January 5, 2016|publisher = History News Network|accessdate=2017-12-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://pacbi.org/pacbi140812/?p=2235|title = Call to Boycott the Oral History Conference at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem: Open Letter |date = August 13, 2013|publisher = Palestinian Campaign for the Academic and Cultural Boycott of Israel |accessdate=2017-12-06 }}</ref>

He received his BA in 1983 from [[Tufts University]]. He received a Ph.D. in history from [[Brandeis University]] in 1989, where he worked under the guidance of [[Donald Worster]], [[David Hackett Fischer]], and [[Morton Horwitz]].

==Publications==
*''Nature Incorporated: Industrialization and the Waters of New England'' (1991). {{ISBN|9780521527118}}
*''Slide Mountain, or the Folly of Owning Nature'' (1995). {{ISBN|9780520207097}}
*''Acts of God: The Unnatural History of Natural Disaster'' (2000). {{ISBN|9780195309683}}
*''Down to Earth: Nature’s Role in American History'' (2002). {{ISBN|9780199797394}}
*''American Green: The Obsessive Quest for the Perfect Lawn'' (2006). {{ISBN|9780393329308}}
*''Gotham Unbound: The Ecological History of Greater New York'' (2014). {{ISBN|9781476741246}}

